  <!-- Section: Common Mistakes -->
  <section id="mistakes" class="scroll-mt-24 mb-12">
    <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold text-neutral-900 mb-4">Common Mistakes to Avoid</h2>

    <div class="space-y-6">
      <div class="border-l-4 border-red-500 pl-4">
        <h3 class="font-semibold text-neutral-900">Underestimating the Business Plan Requirements</h3>
        <p class="text-neutral-600">Austrian authorities take business plans seriously. A generic template or vague concept will likely result in rejection or significant delays. Invest in a professional, Austria-specific business plan that clearly demonstrates economic benefit, market research, and realistic financial projections.</p>
      </div>

      <div class="border-l-4 border-red-500 pl-4">
        <h3 class="font-semibold text-neutral-900">Failing to Prove Investment Fund Sources</h3>
        <p class="text-neutral-600">Austria requires clear documentation of where your €50,000+ investment comes from. Bank statements showing account history, sale agreements, loan documents, or investor commitments are essential. Unexplained large deposits raise red flags.</p>
      </div>

      <div class="border-l-4 border-red-500 pl-4">
        <h3 class="font-semibold text-neutral-900">Neglecting Document Translations and Apostilles</h3>
        <p class="text-neutral-600">Foreign documents need certified German translations and, in many cases, apostilles or legalization. This takes time—start early. Documents in English may be accepted by some offices but German translations are always safer.</p>
      </div>

      <div class="border-l-4 border-red-500 pl-4">
        <h3 class="font-semibold text-neutral-900">Not Engaging with WKO Early</h3>
        <p class="text-neutral-600">The Austrian Economic Chamber (WKO) provides the economic benefit assessment. Consider contacting them informally before applying to understand what they're looking for. Some regional chambers offer pre-consultation services that can strengthen your application.</p>
      </div>

      <div class="border-l-4 border-red-500 pl-4">
        <h3 class="font-semibold text-neutral-900">Ignoring German Language Integration</h3>
        <p class="text-neutral-600">While German isn't required for the initial visa, it matters for permit renewals, permanent residence, and citizenship. Start learning immediately. A1 German is often expected for first renewal; B1 for permanent residence. Vienna offers many German courses for business professionals.</p>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- Section: Healthcare in Austria -->
  <section id="healthcare" class="scroll-mt-24 mb-12">
    <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold text-neutral-900 mb-4">Healthcare in Austria</h2>

    <p class="mb-4">
      Austria has an excellent healthcare system combining mandatory social insurance with optional private coverage. The quality of care is high, facilities are modern, and coverage is comprehensive. As an entrepreneur, you'll likely start with private insurance then transition to the social insurance system once your business is generating income.
    </p>

    <h3 class="text-xl font-semibold text-neutral-900 mb-3">The Austrian Healthcare System</h3>

    <div class="grid md:grid-cols-2 gap-6 mb-6">
      <div class="border border-blue-200 bg-blue-50 rounded-lg p-6">
        <h4 class="font-semibold text-blue-900 mb-3">Social Insurance (ÖGK/SVS)</h4>
        <ul class="space-y-2 text-blue-800">
          <li>• Mandatory for employed and self-employed</li>
          <li>• SVS for self-employed (pension + health + accident)</li>
          <li>• Premium: ~20% of income</li>
          <li>• Comprehensive coverage including hospital</li>
          <li>• Family members can be co-insured</li>
          <li>• Some out-of-pocket costs (Selbstbehalt)</li>
          <li>• Access to all contract doctors and hospitals</li>
          <li>• Prescription medicines partially covered</li>
        </ul>
      </div>

      <div class="border border-green-200 bg-green-50 rounded-lg p-6">
        <h4 class="font-semibold text-green-900 mb-3">Private Insurance (Zusatzversicherung)</h4>
        <ul class="space-y-2 text-green-800">
          <li>• Optional supplement to social insurance</li>
          <li>• Private hospital rooms (Sonderklasse)</li>
          <li>• Free choice of doctors and specialists</li>
          <li>• Shorter waiting times</li>
          <li>• Alternative treatments covered</li>
          <li>• Better dental coverage</li>
          <li>• Premium: €50-300/month depending on age</li>
          <li>• Tax deductible as business expense</li>
        </ul>
      </div>
    </div>

    <h3 class="text-xl font-semibold text-neutral-900 mb-3">Healthcare Quality and Access</h3>

    <p class="mb-4">
      Austrian healthcare consistently ranks among the best in Europe. Key features:
    </p>

    <ul class="list-disc pl-6 space-y-2 mb-6">
      <li><strong>Modern hospitals:</strong> Excellent facilities in Vienna (AKH is one of Europe's largest) and throughout the country</li>
      <li><strong>Qualified doctors:</strong> Rigorous medical training; many doctors speak English, especially in Vienna</li>
      <li><strong>Fast emergency care:</strong> Call 144 for emergencies; excellent response times</li>
      <li><strong>Pharmacy network:</strong> Apotheken widely available; some medicines require prescriptions</li>
      <li><strong>Preventive care:</strong> Annual check-ups covered under social insurance</li>
      <li><strong>Specialist access:</strong> Referral system through GP, though private insurance provides direct access</li>
    </ul>

    <h3 class="text-xl font-semibold text-neutral-900 mb-3">Major Cities Healthcare Notes</h3>

    <div class="grid md:grid-cols-2 gap-6 mb-6">
      <div class="border border-neutral-200 rounded-lg p-6">
        <h4 class="font-semibold text-neutral-900 mb-3">Vienna</h4>
        <ul class="space-y-2 text-neutral-700">
          <li>• Largest medical infrastructure in Austria</li>
          <li>• AKH (Allgemeines Krankenhaus) - major teaching hospital</li>
          <li>• Many English-speaking doctors</li>
          <li>• International expat healthcare practices</li>
        </ul>
      </div>

      <div class="border border-neutral-200 rounded-lg p-6">
        <h4 class="font-semibold text-neutral-900 mb-3">Salzburg</h4>
        <ul class="space-y-2 text-neutral-700">
          <li>• Excellent hospital (Salzburger Landeskliniken)</li>
          <li>• Good specialist access</li>
          <li>• Growing international community</li>
          <li>• Close to German border (additional options)</li>
        </ul>
      </div>

      <div class="border border-neutral-200 rounded-lg p-6">
        <h4 class="font-semibold text-neutral-900 mb-3">Graz</h4>
        <ul class="space-y-2 text-neutral-700">
          <li>• LKH Graz - Styria's main hospital</li>
          <li>• Medical university with research focus</li>
          <li>• Growing tech scene with healthcare support</li>
          <li>• Lower costs than Vienna</li>
        </ul>
      </div>

      <div class="border border-neutral-200 rounded-lg p-6">
        <h4 class="font-semibold text-neutral-900 mb-3">Innsbruck</h4>
        <ul class="space-y-2 text-neutral-700">
          <li>• Excellent mountain rescue and trauma care</li>
          <li>• University hospital</li>
          <li>• Important for outdoor sports enthusiasts</li>
          <li>• Good specialist coverage</li>
        </ul>
      </div>
    </div>

    <div class="bg-blue-50 border border-blue-200 rounded-lg p-4">
      <p class="text-blue-800">
        <strong>E-Card system:</strong> Once enrolled in Austrian social insurance, you'll receive an E-Card—your health insurance card. Present this at doctors and pharmacies for covered treatments. Keep your E-Card updated and carry it at all times. Lost cards can be replaced through your insurance provider.
      </p>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- Section: FAQ -->
  <section id="faq" class="scroll-mt-24 mb-12">
    <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold text-neutral-900 mb-4">Frequently Asked Questions</h2>

    <div class="space-y-6">
      <div class="bg-neutral-50 rounded-lg p-6">
        <h3 class="font-semibold text-neutral-900 mb-2">Does Austria have a Golden Visa program?</h3>
        <p class="text-neutral-600">
          Not in the traditional sense. Austria doesn't offer a straightforward "invest €X in real estate, get residence" program like Portugal or Spain. Instead, Austria has the Red-White-Red Card system for self-employed and investors who demonstrate economic benefit. The minimum investment is around €50,000 for the Self-Employed Key Worker category, but approval depends on your business plan and qualifications, not just the investment amount.
        </p>
      </div>

      <div class="bg-neutral-50 rounded-lg p-6">
        <h3 class="font-semibold text-neutral-900 mb-2">How long does it take to get Austrian citizenship?</h3>
        <p class="text-neutral-600">
          The standard path is 10 years of legal residence. This can be reduced to 6 years with exceptional integration (perfect language skills, community involvement, no public assistance). Austria generally doesn't allow dual citizenship—you'll typically need to renounce your original citizenship. Some exceptions exist for EU citizens and those who automatically gained Austrian citizenship.
        </p>
      </div>

      <div class="bg-neutral-50 rounded-lg p-6">
        <h3 class="font-semibold text-neutral-900 mb-2">Do I need to speak German?</h3>
        <p class="text-neutral-600">
          German isn't required for the initial RWR Card application, but it's increasingly important. For permit renewals, you'll typically need A1-A2 German. For permanent residence, B1 level is required. For citizenship, B2 level plus an Austrian culture/history exam. Vienna's business scene is fairly English-friendly, but German significantly helps with daily life and long-term integration.
        </p>
      </div>

      <div class="bg-neutral-50 rounded-lg p-6">
        <h3 class="font-semibold text-neutral-900 mb-2">Can I bring my family?</h3>
        <p class="text-neutral-600">
          Yes. Your spouse and minor children can accompany you or join later through family reunification. Each family member needs their own residence permit application, but these are processed alongside yours. Spouses receive work rights. Children can attend Austrian schools (excellent public education is free). Each family member needs health insurance unless covered under your Austrian social insurance.
        </p>
      </div>

      <div class="bg-neutral-50 rounded-lg p-6">
        <h3 class="font-semibold text-neutral-900 mb-2">What's the difference between RWR Card and EU Blue Card?</h3>
        <p class="text-neutral-600">
          The EU Blue Card is for highly qualified employees with a job offer meeting salary requirements (€4,752/month in 2026). The RWR Card for Self-Employed is for entrepreneurs starting their own business. If you could work as an employee in a specialized field, the Blue Card offers a simpler path. If you want to build your own company, the RWR Card for Self-Employed is your route.
        </p>
      </div>

      <div class="bg-neutral-50 rounded-lg p-6">
        <h3 class="font-semibold text-neutral-900 mb-2">What happens if my business fails?</h3>
        <p class="text-neutral-600">
          Your RWR Card is tied to self-employment. If your business fails, you'd need to find employment (requires permit change), start a new business, or leave Austria. However, if you've obtained permanent residence (after 5 years), your immigration status isn't affected by business failure. Consider this when planning your long-term timeline.
        </p>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- Section: Final Verdict -->
  <section id="verdict" class="scroll-mt-24 mb-12">
    <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold text-neutral-900 mb-4">Final Verdict</h2>

    <p class="mb-4">
      Austria offers an attractive proposition for entrepreneurs: residence in one of the world's most livable countries without the €500,000+ investment typical of Golden Visa programs. The €50,000 minimum investment for the Self-Employed Key Worker category makes it accessible to serious entrepreneurs, while the Start-up Founder Visa provides a pathway for innovative businesses with accelerator backing.
    </p>

    <p class="mb-4">
      The trade-off is a more rigorous, merit-based process. You'll need a solid business plan, demonstrable economic benefit to Austria, and the willingness to integrate into Austrian society (including learning German). The 10-year path to citizenship is longer than Portugal or Spain, and Austria's requirement to generally renounce original citizenship is a significant consideration.
    </p>

    <p class="mb-6">
      Health insurance is mandatory and represents an ongoing cost. Start with international private insurance for your visa application, then transition to Austrian social insurance once your business is established. Budget €100-400/month depending on coverage level and family situation.
    </p>

    <div class="bg-primary-50 border border-primary-200 rounded-lg p-6">
      <h3 class="font-semibold text-primary-900 mb-3">Bottom Line</h3>
      <p class="text-primary-800 mb-4">
        Austria suits entrepreneurs who prioritize quality of life, central European location, and German-speaking market access over fast citizenship or minimal investment. Come with a genuine business plan, €50,000+ to invest, and commitment to integration. Vienna's growing tech scene and Austria's economic stability make it an excellent base for building a European business—just plan for the longer citizenship timeline.
      </p>
